uhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aLate in the 1930s, the U.S. Department of Agriculture set up a national network of local organizations that joined farmers with public administrators, adult-educators, and social scientists. The aim was to localize and unify earlier New Deal programs concerning soil conservation, farm production control, tenure security, and other reforms, and by 1941 some 200,000 farm people were involved. Even so, conservative anti–New Dealers killed the successful program the next year. This book reexamines the era’s agricultural policy and tells the neglected story of the New Deal agrarian leaders and their visionary ideas about land, democratization, and progressive social change.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aAgriculture and statezUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aDemocratizationzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aFarmersxPolitical activityzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aLand reformzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aLand usexGovernment policyzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aNew Deal, 1933-1939. 0aSocial changezUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aSocial reformerszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aSocial scientistsxPolitical activityzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / United States / 20th Century.2bisacsh1 aRichard, S. Kirkendall, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z97831106725030 cprintz978030020731640uhttps://doi.org/10.12987/978030021339340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300213393423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780300213393/original  a978-3-11-067250-3  Yale University Press Complete 